  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific laws and regulations targeting money laundering. These laws typically aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key examples include:\n\n1. United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. International standards:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n3. Common legal requirements:\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Customer identification protocols\n- Record-keeping requirements for financial institutions\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Typical enforcement mechanisms:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Regulatory sanctions\n\nThese laws generally require financial institutions to implement robust compliance programs and report suspicious activities to prevent money laundering.",
